What difference b/w intermediate Operation and terminal operation?
Intermediate operations in Java Streams are those that transform or filter the data and always return a new stream, allowing multiple operations to be chained together. They are lazy, meaning no actual processing happens until a terminal operation is invoked. Examples include methods like filter(), map(), and sorted(). 

On the other hand, terminal operations mark the end of the stream pipeline and trigger the processing of all intermediate operations. They produce a result or side-effect and do not return a stream. Common terminal operations are collect(), forEach(), count(), and reduce().






What are the method in object class?
Here are the key methods in Java's Object class:
equals(Object obj): Determines if two objects are "equal" based on their content (or identity). 
hashCode(): Returns an integer hash code value for the object. toString(): Returns a string representation of the object. 
getClass(): Returns the Class object representing the class of the object.
clone(): Creates and returns a copy of the object. 
finalize(): Called by the garbage collector when the object is about to be reclaimed. Generally discouraged from use; unpredictable timing.
notify(): Wakes up a single thread that is waiting on this object's monitor.
notifyAll(): Wakes up all threads that are waiting on this object's monitor.
wait(): Causes the current thread to wait until another thread invokes notify() or notifyAll() for this object. 





